--- FEW-SHOT EXAMPLE 1: CONTRACTS (Offer & Acceptance) ---
Facts: Alice posted online that she would sell her 2020 Honda Civic for $12,000. Bob emailed: "I'll pay $11,500." Alice replied: "Deal at $11,800." Bob said nothing for three days, then showed up with $11,800. Alice had already sold to Carol.

{
  "issue": "Whether Alice and Bob formed an enforceable contract for the sale of Alice's Honda Civic at $11,800.",
  "rule_statement": "Under Restatement (Second) of Contracts § 39, a counter-offer is an offer made by the offeree that proposes a substituted bargain, which terminates the original offer. Under § 36, an offeree's power of acceptance terminates upon rejection, counter-offer, lapse, revocation, or the offeror's death. Silence is not acceptance under § 69 unless specific exceptions apply.",
  "rule_exploration": "Courts apply the mirror-image rule: acceptance must match the offer exactly. A reply varying any material term — including price — is a counter-offer that terminates the original offer and reverses the roles of offeror and offeree. (Ardente v. Horan, 117 R.I. 254 (1976)). The offeror may revoke before acceptance. Under § 43, the offeror's conduct inconsistent with the offer terminates it when the offeree learns of that conduct.",
  "application": "Element 1: Was Alice's $11,800 reply an acceptance or a counter-offer?\\nAlice's reply proposed a different price ($11,800 vs. Bob's $11,500). Under the mirror-image rule, this is a counter-offer that terminated Bob's offer and made Alice the new offeror. Counter-argument: one could argue 'Deal' was an acceptance with a request to negotiate price — this fails because Alice explicitly conditioned finality on a new price term.\\n\\nElement 2: Did Bob accept Alice's counter-offer?\\nBob said nothing for three days. Silence is not acceptance under § 69. None of the three exceptions apply (no benefit taken, no prior course of dealing, no silence-as-acceptance term in the offer). Bob's later appearance may constitute conduct, but only if the offer remained open.\\n\\nElement 3: Was Alice's counter-offer still open when Bob appeared?\\nAlice sold to Carol before Bob appeared. Under § 43, an offeror's conduct inconsistent with the offer terminates it when the offeree learns of it. Selling the car to Carol is inconsistent conduct. If Bob had notice, the offer was terminated before his 'acceptance.'",
  "conclusion": "No enforceable contract. Alice's reply was a counter-offer; Bob's silence was not acceptance; Alice's sale to Carol terminated the counter-offer before Bob could accept. Confidence: High — counter-offer and silence rules are well-settled.",
  "tips": ["Students miss that Bob's $11,500 reply itself is a counter-offer — Bob became the original offeree and then offeror simultaneously.", "Do not skip the § 43 revocation analysis — timing of notice is where exam points are lost.", "Cite Restatement sections by number; 'contract law says...' earns no citation credit."]
}

--- FEW-SHOT EXAMPLE 2: TORTS (Negligence) ---
Facts: Dana runs a coffee shop. She mopped the floor near the entrance but placed no wet-floor sign. Erik entered, slipped, fell, and broke his wrist. A regular customer testified the floor was always wet after mopping and no sign was ever posted. Dana argues Erik was looking at his phone when he fell.

{
  "issue": "Whether Dana is liable to Erik in negligence for the injuries he sustained from slipping on the wet floor.",
  "rule_statement": "Under Restatement (Third) of Torts § 3, an actor is negligent when the actor's conduct creates a risk of physical harm and fails to exercise reasonable care. A negligence claim requires: (1) duty, (2) breach, (3) causation (actual and proximate), and (4) damages. A business owner owes a duty of reasonable care to invitees to inspect for and warn of or remedy known or reasonably discoverable dangers. (Restatement (Second) of Torts § 343.)",
  "rule_exploration": "Courts universally hold that business owners owe an invitee a duty of reasonable care, including timely warning of slip hazards. The standard is objective: what would a reasonable person in defendant's position have done? Many jurisdictions apply comparative fault: if plaintiff is partially at fault, damages are reduced proportionally (pure comparative) or barred if plaintiff's fault exceeds 50% (modified comparative). The Learned Hand formula (B < PL) is sometimes invoked: if the burden of precaution (posting a sign) is lower than the probability of harm times magnitude of loss, failure to take precaution is unreasonable.",
  "application": "Element 1: Duty\\nDana operated a coffee shop open to the public. Erik was a business invitee. As a business owner, Dana owed Erik a duty of reasonable care to warn of known hazards on the premises. This element is clearly satisfied.\\n\\nElement 2: Breach\\nDana mopped the floor and created a wet, slippery surface without posting a warning sign. The burden of posting a sign is minimal (B is low). The probability of slipping on an unmarked wet floor in an entrance is reasonably high (P is high), and broken bones are a serious injury (L is high). Under the Learned Hand formula, B < PL: failure to post a sign is unreasonable. The testimony that no sign was ever posted strengthens the breach finding. Counter-argument: Dana may argue the mopping was reasonable maintenance. This fails — it is the absence of a warning, not the mopping itself, that constitutes the breach.\\n\\nElement 3: Causation\\nActual cause: But for Dana's failure to post a warning sign, Erik would have seen the warning and exercised caution, and likely not fallen. Proximate cause: A customer slipping on an unmarked wet floor near the entrance is exactly the type of harm Dana's duty to warn was designed to prevent. No superseding cause breaks the chain.\\n\\nElement 4: Damages\\nErik suffered a broken wrist — a concrete, compensable physical injury. Medical expenses and pain and suffering are recoverable.\\n\\nComparative Fault: Dana argues Erik was on his phone. If the jurisdiction applies modified comparative fault, Erik's contributory negligence (distraction) may reduce his recovery. If his fault exceeds 50%, he may be barred. However, the absence of any warning sign remains the primary cause, and Erik had no reason to anticipate a wet floor without a sign.",
  "conclusion": "Dana is likely liable in negligence. All four elements are satisfied. Damages will be reduced if the jurisdiction applies comparative fault and the jury finds Erik partially responsible for looking at his phone. Confidence: High on liability; Moderate on full recovery given comparative fault question.",
  "tips": ["Students often merge breach and causation — analyze them separately; the exam grader is looking for each element.", "Always address comparative fault if the facts include plaintiff conduct — it is almost always worth points.", "Do not forget proximate cause. 'But for' alone is insufficient; address foreseeability of the type of harm."]
}
"""

